From 450899ccc8da5486ed49aecea34937ce3537a6fb Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Tue, 7 Jul 2026 09:35:05 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 3/3] ogar-from-ruff: Rails-convention association target
 defaulting
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

lift_association() left `class_name` as `None` whenever the Ruby source
had no explicit `class_name:` option, even though Rails itself always
resolves a target class from the association name at load time
(`belongs_to :project` -> `Project`, `has_many :time_entries` ->
`TimeEntry`). Downstream consumers therefore saw an "unresolved"
association target for the common, unadorned case — the real EMIT_ALL
casualty was `belongs_to :project` rendering as an unresolved `?`.

Add default_association_class_name() (+ a small local camelize_snake_case
/ singularize_english_word inflector pair) and call it from
lift_association() only when class_name is still None after option
parsing, so an explicit `class_name:` is never overridden. Skips
polymorphic associations deliberately: their real target is only known
at runtime via the `<name>_type` column, so guessing one from the
association name (`:reactable` -> `Reactable`) would be actively wrong.

The table -> model inflection in ruff_ruby_spo::schema::model_name_for_table
does the same job but is pub(crate) in a crate ogar-from-ruff doesn't
depend on (this crate depends on ruff_spo_triplet / ruff_spo_address, not
ruff_ruby_spo), so it isn't reachable — the local inflector is a small,
independently tested reimplementation of the same convention.

Also updates emit.rs's two Rails-lift integration tests, whose fixtures
declared `has_many :time_entries` with no class_name: they previously
asserted the (now-fixed) wrong `ToMany<TimeEntries>` shape and now assert
the correct `ToMany<TimeEntry>`.

